Trim away any bruises with a knife. Cut vegetables into smaller pieces, at least 1/2-inch (3.8 cm) thick, for easier drying. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/d/d1/Dry-Foods-Step-2Bullet1.jpg/v4-460px-Dry-Foods-Step-2Bullet1.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/d/d1/Dry-Foods-Step-2Bullet1.jpg/v4-760px-Dry-Foods-Step-2Bullet1.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Place 1 quart (0.94 liters) of vegetables into a 36-inch (91 cm) cheesecloth. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/9/99/Dry-Foods-Step-2Bullet2.jpg/v4-460px-Dry-Foods-Step-2Bullet2.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/9/99/Dry-Foods-Step-2Bullet2.jpg/v4-760px-Dry-Foods-Step-2Bullet2.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Blanch the cheesecloth bag of vegetables on the stove in a half-filled pot of boiling water. You may also add 1/4 teaspoon (1.2 ml)of citric acid to the water. Allow up to 6 minutes for blanching, then immediately place the bag in cold water for the same amount of time. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/0/07/Dry-Foods-Step-2Bullet3.jpg/v4-460px-Dry-Foods-Step-2Bullet3.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/0/07/Dry-Foods-Step-2Bullet3.jpg/v4-760px-Dry-Foods-Step-2Bullet3.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Cut the fruit into 1/2-inch (1.27 cm) pieces or in halves to ensure even drying. Fill a large pot with at least 1 quart (0.94 liters) of water. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/c/cb/Dry-Foods-Step-3Bullet1.jpg/v4-460px-Dry-Foods-Step-3Bullet1.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/c/cb/Dry-Foods-Step-3Bullet1.jpg/v4-760px-Dry-Foods-Step-3Bullet1.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Add up to 1.5 teaspoons(7.3 ml) of food-grade quality sodium sulfate or sodium bisulfate to the water. Soak for approximately 5 to 15 minutes, depending on how you sliced the fruit. Rinse the fruit pieces with cold water before placing them on a rack to dry. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/c/cc/Dry-Foods-Step-3Bullet2.jpg/v4-460px-Dry-Foods-Step-3Bullet2.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/c/cc/Dry-Foods-Step-3Bullet2.jpg/v4-760px-Dry-Foods-Step-3Bullet2.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
